<div class="patternContent"><div class="patternTopic"> <h1><a name="Workshop_Templates_and_Variables"></a> Workshop Templates and Variables </h1>
Standards, Templates, Formatting, Variables Presentation for the Document Improvement Workshop.
<p />
<a name="StartPresentation"></a>
<span style="white-space: nowrap"><a href="https://twiki.opensciencegrid.org/bin/view/Documentation/DocumentationTeam/DocImprovementTemplatesVariables?slideshow=on;skin=print;cover=print#GoSlide1"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/SlideShowPlugin/startpres.gif" border="0" alt="Start Presentation" /></a></span>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_1_Introduction"></a> Slide 1: Introduction </span></h2> <ul>
<li> All information for people doing documentation is in <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/DocHowTo" class="twikiLink">DocHowTo</a>
</li> <li> This will cover the Document Formatting Section
</li> <li> We liberally used existing guidelines
</li></ul> 
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_2_Rules_for_topics"></a> Slide 2: Rules for topics </span></h2> <ul>
<li> All topics have a <strong>bold heading</strong> at Level 1 (<code>---+ *Title*</code>) and first letters of words are capitalized (eg. Rules For Formatting Documents).
</li> <li> The level one heading is taken as its twiki topic name, separated into words (e.g., MyTopic becomes My Topic). Choose the twiki name carefully!  If you want to spell out a title whose TWiki name has abbreviations, do that.
</li> <li> All level two sections should be in title case.  Eg: <code>---++ Details on the Installation</code>
</li> <li> All sections (level three and below) have the first word capitalized, the rest lower case.  Eg: <code>---+++ Details on the installation</code> (except for proper nouns)
</li> <li> Exclude from the TOC all sections level three and below (<code>---+++</code>, <code>---++++</code>, etc.).  To accomplish this,  use &#37;TOC{depth="2"}% to produce the table of contents.
</li></ul> 
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_3_Composite_Documents_and"></a> Slide 3: Composite Documents and Templates </span></h2> <ul>
<li> <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/DocExampleMainTopic" class="twikiLink">Documentation.DocExampleMainTopic</a> for a main topic <strong>not likely</strong> to be used with <code>STARTINCLUDE/STOPINCLUDE</code> so as to be included in other topics.
</li> <li> <span class="twikiNewLink">About Includes and Composite Documents<a href="/bin/edit/ReleaseDocumentation/DocFormattingRules?topicparent=Documentation/DocumentationTeam.DocImprovementTemplatesVariables" rel="nofollow" title="About Includes and Composite Documents (this topic does not yet exist; you can create it)">?</a></span>
</li> <li> Wherever possible <a href="https://twiki.grid.iu.edu/twiki/bin/view/TWiki/TextFormattingRules" target="_top">TWiki editing</a> should be used rather than raw HTML.
</li> <li> Here is the WebTopicEditTemplate (now <a href="/bin/view/Trash/ReleaseDocumentationDocInstallTemplate" class="twikiLink">ReleaseDocumentationDocInstallTemplate</a>) for newly created pages in this twiki, which are assumed to be included in other topics.
</li></ul> 
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_4_Screen_View"></a> Slide 4: Screen View </span></h2>
Many documents refer to unix commands, output from a script, a set of lines that should be edited in a file (like a configuration file), or a program listing.  These should be set off in a standard way as follows:
<p />
For a set of commands that can be copied and input or a dump of the screen results from running a script uses a "screen" view:
<pre>
&#60;pre class&#61;&#34;screen&#34;&#62;
command 1
command 2
&#60;/pre&#62;
</pre>
which looks like:
<pre class="screen">
command 1
command 2
</pre>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_5_File_View"></a> Slide 5: File View </span></h2>
For a set of lines in a file to be edited or the contents of a file uses a "file" view:
<pre>
&#60;pre class&#61;&#34;file&#34;&#62;
line 1
line 2
&#60;/pre&#62;
</pre>
which looks like:
<pre class="file">
line 1
line 2
</pre>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_6_Variables"></a> Slide 6: Variables </span></h2>
See <a href="/bin/view/Documentation/DocumentationTeam/WebPreferences" class="twikiLink">WebPreferences</a> for settings of the following variables.
<p /> <ul>
<li> OSG release variable: <strong>%OSG_VERSION%</strong> = 3.x
</li> <li> ITB release variable: <strong>%ITB_VERSION%</strong> = 3.0
</li> <li> VDT release variable: <strong>%VDT_VERSION%</strong> = %VDT_VERSION%
</li> <li> Release variable, according to cache (ITB or OSG): <strong>%VERSION%</strong> = %VERSION%
</li> <li> VDT cache variable: <strong>%VDT_CACHE%</strong> = %VDT_CACHE%
</li> <li> ITB/OSG cache/grid variable: <strong>%CACHE%</strong> = %CACHE% <ul>
<li> Use the  <strong>%CACHE%</strong> variable as a generic reference for either "ITB" or "OSG" <strong>caches</strong>, <strong>grids</strong>, etc.  It automatically expands to "ITB" if its in the Trash/Trash/Integration web, or to "OSG" if its in the production release documentation web.
</li></ul> 
</li> <li> Refer to the cache/version combination that you're using, e.g, %CACHE% %VERSION%, with a space in between, as <br />     <font color="#0000ff"> %CACHE% %VERSION% </font>
</li> <li> Full URL to base of VDT Documentation for current release <strong>%VDT_DOCS_URL%</strong>: %VDT_DOCS_URL%
</li> <li> Full URL to VDT Cache for this release: <strong>%VDT_CACHE_URL%</strong>: %VDT_CACHE_URL%
</li> <li> Full URL to OSG Cache (ITB or Production) for this release <strong>%OSG_CACHE_URL%</strong>: %OSG_CACHE_URL%
</li> <li> Pacman version: <strong>%PACMAN_VERSION%</strong>: %PACMAN_VERSION%
</li></ul> 
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_7_Warnings_and_Notes"></a> Slide 7: Warnings and Notes </span></h2>
<p />
<p />
This describes how to put in a Note, Warning or Important comment that is set off from the regular text. The variables described below are defined in <span class="twikiNewLink">WebPreferences<a href="/bin/edit/Trash/DocumentationTeam/WebPreferences?topicparent=Documentation/DocumentationTeam.DocImprovementTemplatesVariables" rel="nofollow" title="WebPreferences (this topic does not yet exist; you can create it)">?</a></span>.
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_8_Notes"></a> Slide 8: Notes </span></h2>
Notes are asides about the contents of the text that provide specific information that particular, but not all, users may need. Notes are less necessary than <strong>Importants</strong> and unlike <strong>Warnings</strong>, may not cause harm if ignored.
<p /> <ul>
<li> Usage<br>   To create a note, insert the <code>%NOTE%</code> variable, followed by a single space and your text:   <pre>
   &#37;NOTE&#37; Here is my note text.
   </pre>
</li> <li> Example<br>
</li></ul> 
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> NOTE </font></strong> </dt><dd>  Something that I want you to know about and pay some attention to.
</dd></dl> 
<p />
<!-- <code><b>====BEGIN THE SECTION FOR INCLUDING ====</b></code>
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> NOTE </font></strong> </dt><dd> 
</dd></dl> 
<p />
<code><b>==</b></code> END SECTION <code><b>==</b></code> -->
<p />
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_9_Importants"></a> Slide 9: Importants </span></h2>
<strong>Importants</strong> are asides from your normal text that you want to highlight so that skimming users will not ignore them. Unlike Warnings, they will not cause grave harm to the system or the person if ignored. The difference between a <strong>Note</strong> and an <strong>Important</strong> is up to the writer. <ul>
<li> Usage<br>   Importants are included by putting, on a new line, <code>%IMPORTANT%</code> followed by a single space and your important text:   <pre>
   &#37;IMPORTANT&#37; Some text about the important thing.
   </pre>
</li> <li> Example
</li></ul> 
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/warning.gif" alt="ALERT!" title="ALERT!" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#008000"> IMPORTANT </font></strong> </dt><dd>  Don't forget to include a single space or the <strong>Important</strong> will not work.
</dd></dl> 
<p />
<!-- <code><b>==</b></code> BEGIN INCLUDE SECTION <code><b>==</b></code>
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/warning.gif" alt="ALERT!" title="ALERT!" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#008000"> IMPORTANT </font></strong> </dt><dd> 
</dd></dl> 
<p />
<code><b>==</b></code> END SECTION <code><b>==</b></code> -->
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_10_Disclaimers"></a> Slide 10: Disclaimers </span></h2>
<strong>Disclaimers</strong> are asides from your normal text that you want to highlight so that users will not ignore them. Normally they limit the context of the document, its applicability. Unlike warnings, they will not cause grave harm to the system or person if ignored. The difference between a <strong>Note</strong> and an <strong>Important</strong> and a <strong>Disclaimer</strong> is up to the writer.
<p /> <ul>
<li> Usage<br>   Disclaimers are included by putting, on a new line, <code>%DISCLAIMER%</code> followed by a single space and your disclaimer text:   <pre>
   &#37;DISCLAIMER&#37; The content of the disclaimer.
   </pre>
</li></ul> 
<p /> <ul>
<li> Example   %DISCLAIMER% This applies only to documents in this twiki.
</li></ul> 
<p />
<!-- <code><b>==</b></code> BEGIN INCLUDE SECTION <code><b>==</b></code>
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> DISCLAIMER </font></strong> </dt><dd> 
</dd></dl> 
<p />
<code><b>==</b></code> END SECTION <code><b>==</b></code> -->
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_11_Warnings"></a> Slide 11: Warnings </span></h2>
<strong>Warnings</strong> are set off from the regular flow of the text to especially warn the reader about an action that could cause harm to the system or to the user. It's less than something that should be labeled <strong>DANGER</strong> but more harmful than something that you would put into an <strong>Important</strong>. 
<p />
If something that you are instructing a user to do could take up the CPU for several minutes, you should put in a <strong>Warning</strong>. <ul>
<li> Usage<br>   Warnings are added by putting, on a new line, <code>%WARNING%</code> followed by a single space and your text.   <pre>
   &#37;WARNING&#37; Some text here.
   </pre>
</li> <li> Example
</li></ul> 
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/warning.gif" alt="ALERT!" title="ALERT!" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> WARNING! </font></strong> </dt><dd>  If ignore me, you'll regret it.
</dd></dl> 
<!-- <code><b>==</b></code> BEGIN INCLUDE SECTION <code><b>==</b></code>
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/warning.gif" alt="ALERT!" title="ALERT!" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#ff0000"> WARNING! </font></strong> </dt><dd> 
</dd></dl> 
<p />
<code><b>==</b></code> END SECTION <code><b>==</b></code> -->
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Slide_12_Tips"></a> Slide 12: Tips </span></h2>
Tips might be used to suggest an alternative that would be better under certain circumstances. <ul>
<li> Usage<br>   Tips are added by putting, on a new line, <code>%TIP%</code> followed by a single space and your text.   <pre>
   &#37;TIP&#37; Some text here.
   </pre>
</li> <li> Example
</li></ul> 
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#008000"> TIP </font></strong> </dt><dd>  It is really best if you do it this way.
</dd></dl> 
<!-- <code><b>==</b></code> BEGIN INCLUDE SECTION <code><b>==</b></code>
<p /> <dl>
<dt> <img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/help.gif" alt="HELP" title="HELP" width="16" height="16" border="0" />     <strong><font color="#008000"> TIP </font></strong> </dt><dd> 
</dd></dl> 
<p />
<code><b>==</b></code> END SECTION <code><b>==</b></code> -->
